RQ 2 findings

  • Pre-registration traces: There are 1571 volunteers who contributed anonymously before registering for an account. On average there were 9.41 and a standard deviation of 14.17 events, including classifying. Removing classifying events there were on average 0.49 and a standard deviation of 1.7 events.

  • Time to register when contributing anonymously: There are 1439 (91%) volunteers who registered on the first day they joined the project, 132 registered after this time with 45 during the next day.

  • Diversity of pre-registration activities:

cor.test(geordi_summarypre$events, geordi_summarypre$cat_types)

# When users do contribute anonymously what does this behaviour mean for their future participation

Summary of RQ4 results

Sessions when people contribute anonymously (social, task, project) they do the same amount of classifying (outcome variable includes both anon and reg. classifying). When we only look at reg. classifying the difference was significant (further proof linking anonyomus classifications causes different conclusions 49.96946 vs. 42.51292, t = 3.7939, df = 2828.3, p-value = 0.0001514). Using a subset of first session, those who login actually do more classifying 59.36247 vs. 62.73346, but its not significant (t = -1.1232, df = 2366.8, p-value = 0.2614).
